(32, '<img src="uploads/neeraj/articlePic/2015-01-10_09:01:42am_mobile.jpeg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> While some say the earliest â€œwireless phoneâ€ patent was filed by Nathan B. Stubblefield in 1908, the Kentuckianâ€™s vision was really for a cave radio. The first true mobile phone devices were the size of a large briefcase and weighed up to 80 lbs, making them suitable only for in vehicle use, and the first wireless networks were set up to handle just a few callers at any given time, servicing only large cities and highways by the mid forties. <br/> <s>Mobile communications as we know them didnâ€™t come into being until the geniuses at Bell Labs figured out how to create overlapping â€œcellsâ€ which could allow a mobile phone user to remain connected while moving from point to point. (Previously, moving out of range of a wireless tower meant dropping the call.) <br/> <s>Martin Cooper of Motorola is credited with creating the first true â€œcell phoneâ€ in 1983: the Motorola DynaTac 8000X. This is the big phone carried by Michael Douglas in the epic film â€œWall Streetâ€. It was still generally installed in vehicles as it was too big to fit in a pocket, but could be carried outside the vehicle. <br/> <s>Six years later the Motorola MicroTac 9800X came on the market; this phone was small enough (barely) to fit in a jacket pocket. There was still an antenna to pull up, but the bottom half of the phone flipped down and open to reveal the smaller keypad. Julia Roberts carried one in â€œConspiracy Theoryâ€, Kelsey Grammer owned one as â€œFrasierâ€, and Robin Williamsâ€™ MicroTac was buried by the neighborâ€™s dog in the first segment of the movie â€œHookâ€. <br/> <s>Motorola continued to dominate the mobile landscape, coming out with the Motorola International 3200 in 1992. This was the first â€œdigitalâ€ mobile phone, depending on GSM technology instead of the standard analog network. These phones still work today on GSM networks. <br/> <s>Following three years later came the Motorola StarTac - the first true â€œflipâ€ phone (to the delight of Star Trek fans everywhere who had been awaiting the arrival of a real â€œcommunicatorâ€ for years.) The clam-shell StarTac also featured one of the first display screens standard on a cell phone. <br/> <s>Nokia came on the scene in 1992 with the 1011. This was the first mass produced GSM cell phone that could receive SMS (texts). The phone had a memory capable of storing 99 numbers! The 1011 was only produced for 2 years before it was replaced in 1994 by the 2110 - a sleeker model that featured the now famous Nokia ring-tone. <br/> <s>The Nokia 8110 came out in 1996. Instead of a flipping open, the bottom half of the 8110 slid down, creating a elongated curved shape that quickly earned the device the moniker â€œbanana phoneâ€. This phone was used in the first Matrix movie, and became a consumer favorite. <br/> <s>In 1996, Nokia also introduced the Nokia Communicator 9000. This was the worldâ€™s first â€œsmart-phoneâ€. Originally it had a clumsy GEOS operating system, but this was quickly upgraded over the next few years to Symbian. The phone slide open to reveal a full keyboard. Val Kilmer carried one in his role as Simon Templar in â€œSaintâ€. More sophisticated versions appeared in 1998, 2000, and 2002. <br/> <s>Over the past decade, mobile phones have steadily become smaller and smarter, with predictive text function, auto-correct, GPS, and more. Siemens and Samsung soon joined the mobile phone industry, and in 2007 the first iPhone hit the market - selling one million devices in just 74 days. Antennas went internal, and profiles became slimmer and cleaner.'),
(33, '<img src="uploads/rajnish/articlePic/2015-01-10_09:15:58am_decision technique in sports.png.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Each day these technology help referees take the most accurate decisions and viewers around the world to analyze various situations of a game they watch on television or online. <s><br/> <s> <br/> <s>#1. Hawk Eye: This is currently one of the most popular technologies used in the world of sports. It allows tracking the trajectory of the ball, thus helping take correct decisions. The technology is widely used in cricket and tennis and is expected to be used in soccer in 2012, with the starting point being Barclays Premier League. <br/> <s>In tennis the Hawk Eye offers computerized illustrations of the arc of a bouncing ball and identifies the exact position of the ball when it hits the ground, helping the umpire and line judges identify the winner of the point. <br/> <s>It would be interesting to note that the system engages 4 high-speed cameras that take images at different angles around the tennis court and triangulates the location, speed and direction of the ball using the data collected from each cam. <br/> <s>This year FIFA allowed the system to be used to identify <a>quot;goal<a>quot; or <a>quot;no goal<a>quot; situations. The decision was made after the 2010 World Cup, when millions of England fans witnessed Frank Lampard mark a goal in the match against Germany but the referee did not validate it. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>#2. Radar Guns: This technology is also used in tennis. Its goal is to inform viewers about the speed of a player<r>s serve. Although it does not help in taking decisions, it is an interesting source of information for everyone watching a game of tennis, including journalists and those registering World records. <br/> <s>The radars are usually located behind baselines and function on the principle of the Doppler effect, i.e. the faster the tennis ball is going away from the sensor, the more extensive the waves bouncing off the ball will be when they come back. <br/> <s>For a better understanding: when the car approaches you at a high speed you hear the level of noise rising and when it passed you the noise slowly fades away. The same phenomenon was used by astronomers when they came up with the conclusion that our universe is expanding. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>3#. Net-Cord Sensor: The net-cord sensor is not a very complicated technology - it simply translates vibrations into electric power. <br/> <s>It represents a piezoelectric device that makes use of the same technology as a speaker or microphone. <br/> <s>Used in tennis, the gadget is attached to the net in order to signal when a ball has hit the net during a serve. It helps the referee take a decision of whether to call a serve or not. <br/> <s>Here<r>s how it works: when the ball hits the net it generates vibrations that are detected by the sensor and the latter produces a sound signal. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>4#. Computer-Generated Line: This technology is used mainly in football, baseball and soccer. It represents a computer-generated virtual stripe that is projected onto the field and seen only by the TV audience. The line helps viewers get a better understanding on what happened on the field. <br/> <s>In football the virtual line is called the Yellow First Down line and it shows the exact position that the offense must reach for a first down. <br/> <s>The technology is rather complex - in order to project the line it is required to have several cameras, computers and technicians. <br/> <s>In soccer the virtual line allows viewers to see whether a player was in offside position or not. Unfortunately the line cannot influence the decision of the referee and is just there for the TV viewer. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>5#. Instant replay: This technology allows replaying of video footage of a certain event or incident in extremely short time, thus helping judges make important decisions. It is used in live television broadcasting of sports events to show a part of game which was important or notable, or a play that was somewhat unclear on first sight. <br/> <s>A number of sports organizations gave permission to referees to consult replay footage prior to making a decision regarding a dubious play. Such consulting has several name: video referee, video umpire, instant replay official and others. <br/> <s>It would be worth noting that not all sports allow consulting instant video replays. The use of this technology has turned into a debate among the officials and sports fans of soccer, with the officials refusing to make use of it as it could have serious impact on the specific aspects of associated football. However, instant replay is sometimes used for taking disciplinary decisions. The technology is officially used in football, basketball, field hockey, baseball, cricket and more.'),
(34, '<img src="uploads/neeraj/projectnotesPic/2015-01-10_09:55:51am_SmartMan-wearable-electronic-system.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/>  <br/> <s>Wearable is for sure the Next Big thing in ICT industry but these are not limited to watches, bracelets and glasses, here we are talking bout smart clothing. Yes, you read it correct smart clothing, your shirt, your trousers and even your Gloves will be smart. Lets take a sneak peak at what future holds for us and what is already present for us to use. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>perfect example of next-generation wearable tech is Cityzen Sciencesâ€™ project, codename D-Shirt. Sensors which detect movement, heart rate, speed, breathing patterns, and GPS location are woven into the fabric of this high-tech shirt, which should go on sale in 2015 as both a top and a pair of cycling shorts. In development since 2012, itâ€™s not the shirt that makes this important, itâ€™s the fabric. By perfecting such a new forms of fabric, the technology that makes wristbands so popular may weave itself into our clothes. <br/> <s>â€œSmartshirts can hold more sensors closer to the skin,â€ explained Gartnerâ€™s research director to The Guardian. â€œThey can collect more information and produce better data, like the full wave of the heart beat rather than just the pulse.â€ <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Integrating technology into clothing doesnâ€™t have to be about measuring fitness. The Visijax Commuter Jacket uses technology to improve a cyclistâ€™s safety. A Teflon coating makes it waterproof, and all-round ventilation keeps the wearer cool, but this isnâ€™t the techy part. A rechargeable battery pack powers a set of white and red LED lights, and car-style indicators which activate automatically, even if the rider has both hands on the handlebars. The Visijax uses wearable technology to solve a very real problem, and one that is becoming more widespread in cities around the world. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The AMPL SmartBackpack shares a waterproof covering, and a removable battery pack, with the Visijax, but is designed for convenience. USB cables in each pocket charge gadgets stored in the backpack â€” from a phone to a laptop â€” and an app keeps you informed of levels. It also has the ability to adjust priority and sound an alert should the bag get left behind. Calling something smart isnâ€™t only about connecting it with a smartphone, itâ€™s also about smartly solving problems, and keeping gadgets topped up with energy is a constant issue. <br/> <s>Where tech and fashion begin to meet <br/> <s>LikeAGlove is one example. You order one basic piece of clothing from the company, but itâ€™s only supposed to be worn inside the house, because itâ€™s only for taking your exact measurements. Working with online stores, LikeAGlove will ensure the clothes you order online will fit you perfectly, taking away one of the biggest frustrations in shopping for clothes over the Internet: not being absolutely sure about sizing. The company told CNet that a production model should be ready for early 2015. <br/> <s>The fashion world is only now beginning to explore smart concepts, but we could start to see clothing with features similar to the Synapse Dress, in designs we could actually wear out on the street. Made using Intelâ€™s Edison chip, the wearer could control the built-in lighting system and video camera using their brainwaves. Smart clothing is as much about fun and creativity as safety, fitness, and convenience. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>These smart clothes arenâ€™t only for fashion-conscious adults either. The Exmobaby is a pair of smart pajamas for babies, containing a thermometer, movement sensors, and a special ECG monitor woven into the fabric. Itâ€™ll help parents keep an eye on the childâ€™s well-being, and cleverly uses an FM transmitter to send data to an external station, keeping any electronics at a safe distance. The station also doubles as a nightlight. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Tantalizingly close to reality <br/> <s>Smart clothing like Bowkerâ€™s wild designs and the Synapse Dress are only fit for fashion shows and runways, but as with most clothing trends, thatâ€™s where it all starts. Donâ€™t forget, Ralph Lauren has experimented with smart clothes; weâ€™ve tried on attention-grabbing LED screened t-shirts, and there are performance tracking bras already. Basic smart clothes are already here. <br/> <s>Thereâ€™s still plenty of work to be done, especially in the areas of battery power and miniaturization of hardware, before smart clothing hits the mainstream. However, we can already see smart fabrics, clothing, and inks are attracting attention from a very diverse crowd. Taking it out of the tech industryâ€™s hands means more variety, and a better chance weâ€™ll get something we actually want to wear everyday. If things work out as analysts expect, by the end of 2016, weâ€™ll buy more smart clothes than any other kind of wearable tech. This yearâ€™s CES might be the place where weâ€™ll get our first look at the trends tech fans will be wearing next year. <br/> <s> <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Reffer: http://www.digitaltrends.com/wearables/smart-clothing-garments-at-ces-2015-and-beyond/'),
(35, '<img src="uploads/rahul/articlePic/2015-01-10_11:32:34am_angry-woman.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> 1. <s>They canâ€™t help it: <s><br/> <s> <s> <s>Angry people have lots of excuses. Women will blame their PMS. Both sexes will blame their stress, their exhaustion, or their worries. Never mind that other people who have PMS or who are stressed, tired, or worried donâ€™t pop off at the world. Angry people donâ€™t yet understand that they are actually giving themselves permission to rant. In that sense, they are very much in control. <br/> <s> <s> <s> <br/> <s>2. The only way to express anger is to explode: <s><br/> <s> <s> People who rage believe that anger is like the buildup of steam in an overheated steam engine. They think they need to blow off the steam in order to be OK. In fact, raging tends only to produce more of the same. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>3. Frustration is intolerable: <br/> <s> <s> Angry people canâ€™t sit with frustration, anxiety or fear. To them, such feelings are a signal that they are being challenged. When life doesnâ€™t go their way, when someone doesnâ€™t see things as they do, when their best-laid plans get interrupted or they make a mistake, they simply canâ€™t tolerate it. To them, itâ€™s better to blow than to be left with those feelings. They donâ€™t get it that frustration is a normal part of everyoneâ€™s life and that it is often the source of creativity and inspiration. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>4. Itâ€™s more important to win than to be right: <s><br/> <s> <s>Chronically angry people often have the idea that their status is at stake when there is conflict. When questioned, they take it overly personally. If they are losing an argument, they experience a loss of self-esteem. At that moment, they need to assert their authority, even if they are wrong. When it is certain that they are wrong, they will find a way to prove that the other person is more wrong. For mature people, self-esteem is grounded in being able to put ego aside in order to find the best solution. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>5. â€œRespectâ€ means that people do things their way: <s><br/> <s> <s>When another driver tailgates, when a partner refuses to go along with a plan, when a kid doesnâ€™t jump when told to do something, they feel disrespected. To them, disrespect is intolerable. Making a lot of noise and threatening is their way of reasserting their right to â€œrespectâ€ by others. Sadly, when the basis of â€œrespectâ€ is fear, it takes a toll on love and caring. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>6. The way to make things right is to fight: <s><br/> <s> <s>Some angry people have learned at the feet of a master. Having grown up with parents who fight, it is their â€œnormal.â€ They havenâ€™t a clue how to negotiate differences or manage conflict except by escalating. Then they become very much like the parent they loathed and feared when they were kids. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>7. Other people should understand that they didnâ€™t mean what they did or said when they were angry: <s><br/> <s> <s> Angry people feel that anger entitles them to let loose. Itâ€™s up to other people not to take seriously hurtful things they say or do. After all, they say, they were just angry. They donâ€™t get it that other people are legitimately hurt, embarrassed, humiliated, or afraid. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Source: http://psychcentral.com/lib/7-mistaken-assumptions-angry-people-make/00012480 '),
(36, '<img src="uploads/neeraj/projectnotesPic/2015-01-10_11:43:07am_EPC image.gif" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/>  <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Network Functions Virtualization (NFV) is today the most talked about technology in telecom research circle. This technology will be applied to virtually all parts of telecommunications <s>network and the Evolved Packet Core (EPC), it also one of the more concrete examples of how NFV can be utile in a carrier network. <br/> <s>Virtual EPC was a first talked about and demonstrated at the 2013 Mobile World Congress, by Cisco, NEC, and Intel. At MWC 2014 event it was the biggest networking story at the show. AT<a>amp;T<r>s announced that it will soon work with virtual EPC startup Affirmed Networks epitomized this. <br/> <s>The Evolved Packet Core (EPC) is the 3GPP-specified core network for Long Term Evolution (LTE) access. Over time, it will also become a common core network for packet-switched services in 2G and 3G networks, and potentially for Wi-Fi access. The EPC is central to the mobile network architecture and critical to the delivery of end-user services. It sits between the radio access network (RAN), the IP network, external services and a number of other network elements used to authenticate, secure and deliver services to end users. It is a strategic point of control in the delivery of mobile data services, as shown in the excerpt below. <s><br/> <s>All of the technology vendors are now on board with the concept of virtual EPC, and large vendors â€“ as well as a number of challengers â€“ now have plans to offer commercial product. In detail, however, there are significant differences between suppliers, both in approach and in timing. This report examines 11 leading EPC technology vendors, detailing their virtual EPC strategy, technology and timeline. <s><br/> <s>Many mobile core functions have been identified as good candidates for virtualization, and it is not unrealistic to think that an entire mobile core could be fully virtualized and operate at close to parity in performance and feature terms with traditional core network within three years. Feature parity could be achieved in a shorter time frame, and a <a>quot;good enough<a>quot; feature set even sooner. The excerpt below identifies three categories of mobile core functions: The packet gateway (a bearer-plane function) in red; control-plane nodes (MME, Policy, IMS, etc.) in yellow; and Gi-LAN functions circled in blue. <s> '),
(37, '<a href="uploads/tarant8l/files/2015-01-10_08:40:24pm_x001.pdf" ><img src= "img/pdf.jpg" style= "max-width: 100%;" /></a>  \n<br/> 10 donâ€™ts in Astrology #2015shift #VenuSign #HeilHydra <s><br/> <s> <br/> <s>The text was compiled in order to spare you the ordeals of superstition in the year 2015, with Venus entering Hydra. The hash tags will help you with your research. <s><br/> <s> <br/> <s>1)	Avoid 12. By all means, avoid â€œ12 ascendantsâ€. There are good reasons to avoid 12 ascendants superstitions, such as regaining your own guardian angel. Gemini has been shifting towards the north of your horoscope over the past 5000 years: therefore, when they say you had a â€œGemini ascendantâ€, youâ€™ll find said twin stars at north instead. That only makes for 90 degrees of miscalculation. You wonâ€™t spot Gemini rising at east. So drop the 12. #QuarterSky #ZodiacShift #ZodiacFix #AcademicZodiac #AscendantShift #HGA #16ascendants guardian #angels <br/> <s>2)	Avoid 13. The number of zodiacal stations is 22. The ascendants are 16. Anyone can see them with naked eye. The Sun does not determine the zodiac: the planets do. And, by the way, Ophiuchus happens to be one of the 16 ascendants. #2016shift #Saturn in #Ophiuchus #Ofiuco 1622 <br/> <s>3)	#SunSigns are generally unimportant, however 16 by extension; including Orion, Cetus and Sextans. <br/> <s>4)	The lunar calendar may not be what they hold in their own hands at all: thus â€“ 9-11 has Moon in Orion. <s><br/> <s>5)	Venus sign may be important for you. Thus, in the year 2015, Venus enters Hydra â€“ compare it with e.g. your partnerâ€™s Mars in Cetus. #VenuSign #Venus in #Hydra #2015shift <s><br/> <s>6)	The #ZodiacShift is non-linear much as the #AscendantShift â€“ these have nothing to do with anything as expected in popular mind. The zodiac shift thus travels by precession towards fantastic seven signs of solar shift, while an example has been given as concern the ascendant shift already â€“ Gemini last rose at