(201, '<a href="uploads/rajnish/files/2015-02-05_12:20:28pm_A Survey on Software Clone Detection Research.pdf" ><img src= "img/pdf.jpg" style= "max-width: 100%;" /></a>  \n   <br/>  <s>Supposing the vast amount of repeated code and its maintenance cost of large software systems, it is essential to find program segment clones of large systems for doing the respective maintenance tasks (e.g., refactoring).Much research has been done to find code clones automatically. Again, the same question come into existence of the definition of program segment clone itself. In so many instances, one canâ€™t be sure that some program fragment is copied from another. There are lots of code clones in software systems and â€œcopy paste modifyâ€ programming approaches are common method in software development as said by (Li <a>amp; Sun, 2010). This kind of behavior is wrong, hard to assure and not well established as genuine so it will produce software maintenance difficulties including but not limited to the specified: Â  <br/> <s>Â Â  Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â â€¢ Program code fragment obstacles spread out wider and quicker. It becomes more worst if the programmer is not having knowledge of these similarities. Â  <br/> <s>Â Â  Â  <br/> <s>Â Â â€¢ Program code fragment logical consistent across having the same code slices is volatile. Â  <br/> <s>Â Â  Â  <br/> <s>Â Â â€¢ Program code fragment increase without any necessity which lifts the effort of understands the system. Â  <br/> <s>Â Â  Â  <br/> <s>Â Â â€¢ Code fragment cloning rises the size of software systemâ€™s there by putting a strain on system resource, it Â degrade the overall functioning in terms of execution time and execution of space requirement also degrade performance of compilation time requirements. Â  <br/> <s>Â Â  Â  <br/> <s>Â Â Without knowing about how and where the fragments of code are reused, if there are bugs in any fragment, that bugs will also be reflected in the reused fragments. Thus it becomes essential from maintenance point of view to know which parts within the code are copied or reused. Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â There exists some different techniques to detect clone which have good precision but poor recall and vice versa. Some techniques are scalable while other has fast detection time. Most of the techniques are limited to small programs only. Some are infeasible for larger programs and detects only exact clones. So, there is a need for an efficient clone detection technique in larger programs that can deal with different type of clones. Â  Â  <br/> <s>Â Â  Â  <br/> <s>Â Â There are many code clone detection techniques each having its own advantages and disadvantages. These techniques are Text based, Token-based, Abstract Syntax tree based, Metric based and Program dependency graph (PDG) based detection technique. Most of the existing hybrid techniques used abstract syntax tree-based detection (AST) and program dependency graph (PDG). The complexity of comparison approach in these techniques increases with rise in the size of the code. The metric based detection technique is more scalable and accurate for large software system. Token based technique can find up to Type 3 clones with high accuracy and confidence. Also, hashing always reduces the complexity of any algorithm. Thus, if hashing is integrated with token based clone detection technique, the complexity of comparison will definitely reduce. '),
(202, '<img src="uploads/rajnish/projectnotesPic/2015-02-05_12:15:48pm_techniwues os clone detection.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Software clone detection is mainly implemented for the restructuring, maintenance, refactoring and reengineering of software (Raheja <a>amp; Tekchandani, 2013) (Roy <a>amp; Cordy, 2007). By detecting clones, the computation cost and complexity of the software system can be minimized. Because of these factors software clone detection is new and an important research area. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>1)	Textual based approach <br/> <s>2)	Token based approach <br/> <s>3)	Abstract syntax tree approach <br/> <s>4)	Program dependency graph based approach <br/> <s>5)	Metric based approach <s><br/> <s>6)	Hybrid based approach <br/> <s> <br/> <s>1. TEXTUAL BASED APPROACH: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Two program code fragments are comparing with each other to find matched sequence of text or strings. If match is found then code is a clone pair by the detection technique. Some popular tool that are used for this technique are Duploc (Ducasse, et al., 1999), DuDe (Wettel <a>amp; Marinescu, 2005), Simian (Rattan, et al., 2013), SDD (Similar data detection) (Lee, 2005), NICAD (Roy <a>amp; Cordy, 2008) (Roy, 2009). Duploc is languages independent clone detection tool in which no parsing required. DuDe is line based clone detection tool. Line base comparisons are done by using dynamic pattern matching and result is display in sort of dot plot (Rattan, et al., 2013). Simian is used to find clone in different programming language. If Simian is does not able to distinguish programming language of the actual file, then it treat it as a plain text files to detect clones. SDD is used for detecting code clone in large size systems. Nicad is a text based hybrid clone detection tool and it is able to find near-miss clones. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>2. TOKEN BASED APPROACH: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>It needs a parser or lexical analysis to normalize the code in form of token. So every line of source code is converted into token then comparison applied on intermediate representation. The sequences of lines are compared through different algorithms. This technique is slower than text based approach and it is more robust. Some popular tools that are used for this technique are CCFinder (Kamiya, et al., 2002), CP-Miner (Lu, et al., 2006), FCFinder (Sasaki, et al., 2010), CCFinderX (Kamiya, n.d.), ConQAT (Juergens, et al., 2010)etc. CCFinder (Code Clone Finder) uses a suffix tree matching algorithm to detect similar subsequence. CP-Miner uses frequent item-set mining to find bugs in the software made by cloning. FCFinder uses hashing to detect clones which are copied across projects. FCFinder took a long time to detect file clones in the 10GB collection. CCFinderX is used to study code clone genealogies at release level. It is also used it for analysis of the relation between open source software quality and code cloning. <s><br/> <s> <br/> <s>3. ABSTRACT SYNTAX TREE APPROACH: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The actual source code is parsed into abstract syntax tree (AST) or parse tree and traverse the tree for finding similar sub tree. If match is found for sub tree is termed as clone. AST representation better understands but very complex to create an abstract syntax tree and expensive process on both time and memory. Some popular tool that are used for this technique are CloneDR (Baxter, et al., 1998), Deckard (Jiang, et al., 2007), SimScan, and ClemanX (Nguyen, et al., 2009). CloneDR is used to find exact and near-miss clone by taking help of hashing and dynamic programming. SimScan is variation of CloneDR. Deckard is used for computing characteristics vector from AST and clustering vector. It is also used to finding refactoring on parts of a clone in open source systems. <s> <br/> <s> <br/> <s>4. PROGRAM DEPENDENCY GRAPH BASED APPROACH: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>It shows the control flow and data dependencies. When PDG is obtained from source code an isomorphic graph comparison is applied to find similarity. PDG contains the control flow and data flow information of a program and hence carries semantic information. After obtain a set of PDGs are obtained from a subject program, isomorphic subgraph matching algorithm is applied for finding similar subgraphs which are returned as clones. For big software it is very difficult to obtain PDG. Some popular tool that are used for this technique are Duplix (Krinke, 2001), PDG-DUP (Komondoor, 2001), and Scorpio etc. (Rattan, et al., 2013). Duplix works on the k-limiting approach of finding maximal similar subgraphs. PDG-DUP is also a PDG-based tool which uses program slicing to find isomorphic graphs. It also helps in detecting non-contiguous. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>5. METRIC BASED APPROACH: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Instead of comparing code directly calculate metric from source code are obtained and these metric are compared to detect clone. To calculate metric there are many software that are used such as Columbus, Source Monitor, Datrix etc. This technique is more salable and accurate for big software system. Some popular tool that are used for this technique are CLAN (Patenaude, et al., 1999), Columbus, Source monitor, Mossegager (BÂ¨uhler, 2003), Datrix, and MCD Finder etc. The metric which are extracted from source code are compared to assess similarity. CLAN is one of the first approach to compare metrics obtained from an AST of source code. CLAN widely used in the last decade. Columbus is the tool which provides metrics that are useful in detecting clones, but this tool does not work for JAVA programs. The tool available for calculating JAVA code metrics is Source Monitor (Bhide, 2009) but the metrics provided by this tool are not efficient in providing the result of code clone detection. Datrix tool is available for calculating JAVA code metrics are highly complex, which are designed for extending the quality of JAVA code (Patenaude, et al., 1999). MCD Finder is a tool that are useful for predicting clones in the JAVA software and it is easy to use. <s><br/> <s> <br/> <s>6. HYBRID BASED APPROACH: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Hybrid based clone detection technique is quite complex but it is very effective technique for detecting clones in software artifacts as compare to above said technique. In this techniques two or more existing clone detection technique are combined to find clone of code. Clone detection technique that uses combinations of syntactic and semantic characteristic is called hybrid clone detection technique. PDG (Ferrante, et al., 1987) contains the control flow and data flow information of a program and hence carries semantic information. Once a set of PDGs are obtained from a subject program, isomorphic subgraph matching algorithm is applied for finding similar subgraphs which are returned as clones. There are some tools such as PDG-DUP, Duplix and Scorpio etc. Duplix (Kim, et al., 2006) works on the k-limiting approach of finding maximal minimal subgraphs. PDG-DUP (Karp <a>amp; Richard, 1986) is also a PDG based tool which uses program slicing to find isomorphic subgraphs. <s>It also helps in detecting non-contiguous clones. Scorpio applied for two way slicing to detect clones. The tool currently works on for JAVA and is based on number of PDG specialization for JAVA language and heuristics to speed up the overall detection process.'),
(203, '<img src="uploads/rajnish/projectnotesPic/2015-02-05_12:39:54pm_MITConcurrentQueues.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Parallelizing common algorithms: <br/> <s>	Researchers revamp a common <a>quot;data structure<a>quot; so that it will work with multicore chips. <br/> <s>	Every undergraduate computer-science major takes a course on data structures, which describes different ways of organizing data in a computerâ€™s memory. Every data structure has its own advantages: Some are good for fast retrieval, some for efficient search, some for quick insertions and deletions, and so on. <br/> <s>Today, hardware manufacturers are making computer chips faster by giving them more cores, or processing units. But while some data structures are well adapted to multicore computing, others are not. In principle, doubling the number of cores should double the efficiency of a computation. With algorithms that use a common data structure called a priority queue, thatâ€™s been true for up to about eight cores â€” but adding any more cores actually causes performance to plummet. <br/> <s>At the Association for Computing Machineryâ€™s Symposium on Principles and Practice of Parallel Programming in February, researchers from MITâ€™s Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory will describe a new way of implementing priority queues that lets them keep pace with the addition of new cores. In simulations, algorithms using their data structure continued to demonstrate performance improvement with the addition of new cores, up to a total of 80 cores. <br/> <s>A priority queue is a data structure that, as its name might suggest, sequences data items according to priorities assigned them when theyâ€™re stored. At any given time, only the item at the front of the queue â€” the highest-priority item â€” can be retrieved. Priority queues are central to the standard algorithms for finding the shortest path across a network and for simulating events, and theyâ€™ve been used for a host of other applications, from data compression to network scheduling. <br/> <s>With multicore systems, however, conflicts arise when multiple cores try to access the front of a priority queue at the same time. The problem is compounded by modern chipsâ€™ reliance on caches â€” high-speed memory banks where cores store local copies of frequently used data. <br/> <s><a>quot;As you are reading the front of the queue, the whole front of the queue will be in your cache,â€ says Justin Kopinsky, an MIT graduate student in electrical engineering and computer science and one of the new paperâ€™s co-authors. â€œAll of these guys try to put the first element in their cache and then do a bunch of stuff with it, but then somebody writes to it, and it invalidates everybody elseâ€™s cache. And this is like an order-of-magnitude slowdown â€” maybe multiple orders of magnitude.<a>quot; <br/> <s>Loosening up: <br/> <s>To avoid this problem, Kopinsky; fellow graduate student Jerry Li; their advisor, professor of computer science and engineering Nir Shavit; and Microsoft Researchâ€™s Dan Alistarh, a former student of Shavitâ€™s, relaxed the requirement that each core has to access the first item in the queue. If the items at the front of the queue can be processed in parallel â€” which must be the case for multicore computing to work, anyway â€” they can simply be assigned to cores at random. <br/> <s>But a core has to know where to find the data item itâ€™s been assigned, which is harder than it sounds. Data structures generally trade ease of insertion and deletion for ease of addressability. You could, for instance, assign every position in a queue its own memory address: To find the fifth item, you would simply go to the fifth address. <br/> <s>But then, if you wanted to insert a new item between, say, items four and five, youâ€™d have to copy the last item in the queue into the first empty address, then copy the second-to-last item into the address you just vacated, and so on, until youâ€™d vacated address five. Priority queues are constantly being updated, so this approach is woefully impractical. <br/> <s>An alternative is to use whatâ€™s known as a linked list. Each element of a linked list consists of a data item and a â€œpointerâ€ to the memory address of the next element. Inserting a new element between elements four and five is then just a matter of updating two pointers. <br/> <s>Road less traveled: <br/> <s>The only way to find a particular item in a linked list, however, is to start with item one and follow the ensuing sequence of pointers. This is a problem if multiple cores are trying to modify data items simultaneously. Say that a core has been assigned element five. It goes to the head of the list and starts working its way down. But another core is already in the process of modifying element three, so the first core has to sit and wait until itâ€™s done. <br/> <s>The MIT researchers break this type of logjam by repurposing yet another data structure, called a skip list. The skip list begins with a linked list and builds a hierarchy of linked lists on top of it. Only, say, half the elements in the root list are included in the list one layer up the hierarchy. Only half the elements in the second layer are included in the third, and so on. <br/> <s>The skip list was designed to make moving through a linked list more efficient. To find a given item in the root list, you follow the pointers through the top list until you identify the gap into which it falls, then move down one layer and repeat the process. <br/> <s>But the MIT researcher<r>s algorithm starts farther down the hierarchy; how far down depends on how many cores are trying to access the root list. Each core then moves some random number of steps and jumps down to the next layer of the hierarchy. It repeats the process until it reaches the root list. Collisions can still happen, particularly when a core is modifying a data item that appears at multiple levels of the hierarchy, but they become much rarer. <br/> <s> <br/> <s> The original article was written by Larry Hardesty https://newsoffice.mit.edu/2015/new-priority-queues-data-structure-0130 <br/> <s>Reviewed http://phys.org/news/2015-01-parallelize-common-multicore-chips.html'),
(204, '<img src="uploads/deshu/projectnotesPic/2015-02-05_01:27:34pm_CMCD.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Y. Yuan and Krinke proposed a CMCD method for count matrix based clone detection, which is generated while counting the rate of frequencies of every variable in conditions specified by pre-determined counting condition. The proposed technique is language-independent as it depends only on variable count. Counting condition is used to select when the count should begin. That is, if we have to count the rates of frequencies of variable in certain circumstances with special standards, these standards are called as counting condition. The count matrix (CM) is a collection of n count vectors (CV) and compares these Counting vectors with the help of Euclidean space. The variation between two vectors is calculated by the Euclidian Distance. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>	The CMCD is count matrix, which is created while counting the occurrence frequencies of every variable in situations specified by pre-determined counting conditions. <s><br/> <s> <br/> <s>	The CMCD is language-independent because it depends only on variable counts. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>	Counting conditions are used to decide when to count. That is, if we decide to count the occurrences of variable in certain circumstances with special criteria, this criterion is called a counting condition. <s><br/> <s> <br/> <s>	Compare the CVs in the Euclidean space. The difference between two vector is determined by the Euclidian Distance between them in the space. <br/> <s>	 <br/> <s>Conclusion: <br/> <s>	The CMCD perform well in extracting count-based information and it is language independent. It helps to detect clone in large programs (<a>gt; 1M LoC) also it has a capabilities to perform well in scenario-based evaluation. <br/> <s> <s> <s> Capabilities where it perform well: <br/> <s>a.	Performs well in scenario-based evaluation. <br/> <s>b.	Detects code plagiarism in studentsâ€™ homework. <br/> <s>c.	Identifies a potential bug in JDK source code.'),
