witter feed, though has done publicly posted tweets searchable and accessible around Google search. <br/> <s>In comments to Search Engine Land during that time, Google had remarkable that it designed to relaunch real-time hunt with live information streams from mixed sources. But a association did not give any denote when it designed to do that. The new partnership with Twitter suggests that Google competence be formulation on relaunching a use soon. <br/> <s>News of a partnership between a dual companies sent Twitterâ€™s batch adult Thursday, with some financial analysts observant it as a jointly profitable arrangement for a dual companies. <br/> <s>A JPMorgan researcher quoted in Investorâ€™s Business Daily called a partnership a certain pierce that could assistance Twitter boost a series of purebred users and give Google entrance to some-more user- and social-generated content. <br/> <s>Reference: http://www.eweek.com/cloud/google-confirms-twitter-partnership-for-real-time-tweets-in-search.html'),
(206, '<img src="uploads/shruti/projectnotesPic/2015-02-06_07:55:16am_youtubemultiview.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Ever watch a YouTube video, and wish you could see things differently? <br/> <s>Well, now you can. The popular online video service announced a new feature on Wednesday that lets users upload multiple camera angles for a YouTube video. Viewers can then switch camera angles on the fly as they watch. <br/> <s>So far there<r>s only one video you can try it out on, a live performance of artist Madilyn Bailey, though YouTube is taking requests from others that want to help test the feature. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The multiple views show up as thumbnails alongside the main video and disappear once it gets started. Users can hop between the cameras by clicking on the different cameras, or by using keyboard shortcuts. In practice, this causes small jitters in the playback, which can be mitigated by holding down a key for a second or so, something YouTube is encouraging people to try out. <br/> <s>YouTube is not the first to try out this feature. There<r>s Streamweaver( http://streamweaver.com/ ) as well as the now-defunct Switchcam. Additionally, YouTube has been testing support for up to six cameras for users of its live event broadcasting, though users couldn<r>t hop between them after the fact. <br/> <s>Reference: http://tech.firstpost.com/news-analysis/youtube-testing-a-new-multi-angle-feature-for-videos-253208.html <s> http://www.delhidailynews.com/news/YouTube-testing-new-multi-angle-feature-for-videos-1423206182/'),
(207, '<img src="uploads/mridula/challengePic/2015-02-06_08:33:29am_freewifizone.jpeg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /> <br/> Kolkata will take its first tentative step towards turning into a Wi-Fi city on Thursday. The city<r>s first Wi-Fi hotspot will be inaugurated at Park Street by chief minister Mamata Banerjee, paving the way for a gradual rollout in the rest of Kolkata by early 2016. To be provided by Reliance JIO, the service will initially be free of charge and could next be made available in the Gariahat-Gol Park area of south Kolkata. Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â Â  Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â Â All of Kolkata will have WiFi by April end, making the City of Joy the first WiFi enabled metro in India: Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â Â  Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â Â According to the chief minister, Reliance Jio has already laid 2,000 km of underground optic fibre in Kolkata and another 250300 km is left, which would be over in weeks and Kolkata will be Wi-Fi enabled by April-end. Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â Â â€œKolkata is countryâ€™s first Wi- Fi city and worldâ€™s first knowledg e hub,â€ Mamata proudly announced after the inauguration. Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â Â  Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â Â Once the Park Street hotspot is flagged off, adjoining roads like Loudon Street, Camac Street, Mirza Ghalib Street and Rafi Ahmed Kidwai Road will be covered, too. This, in effect, means anyone with a Wi-Fi-enabled device can log on to the Internet, using a password that will be announced. You don<r>t need a 4G connection to avail the service. It frees the users from the burden of a datacard. Smartphone users will be able to log in merely by clicking on the Wi-Fi option. Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â Â  Â  <s><br/> <s>Â Â Â References: http://www.telegraphindia.com/1150128/jsp/calcutta/story_10332.jsp#.VNR6qNKUeyl Â  http://www.hindustantimes.com/kolkata/park-street-goes-wi-fi/article1-1314144.aspx'),
(208, '<img src="uploads/rahul/challengePic/2015-02-06_08:47:20am_Screen-Shot-2015-02-05-at-8_png.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /> <br/> This one might be a show for kids thatâ€™s just as fun for adults to watch. Google has partnered with Disney to make a new cartoon series, Miles from Tomorrowland, to inspire kids to code. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>In this outer space adventure, Miles explores the galaxy with his family and best friend in tow. Milesâ€™ family joins him for the ride, including his mom and ship captain, Phoebe, his mechanical engineer dad, Leo, his tech-savvy big sister, Loretta, and his best friend and pet robo-ostrich Merc. The show is designed to not only fuel kidsâ€™ interest in space but also coding, teamwork, critical thinking and exploration. The showâ€™s makers tapped consultants from NASA, Space Tourism Society and Google to keep it real. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Characters are voiced by a stellar cast, too, including Olivia Munn, Adrian Grenier, Mark Hamill, George Takei, Bill Nye, Wil Wheaton, Alton Brown and Brenda Song. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The seriesâ€™ premiere is tomorrow, Feb. 6, on the Disney Channel, starting at 9 a.m. PT. You can watch four back-to-back episodes, each featuring space facts integrated into the storylines of Milesâ€™ missions as he strives to â€œconnect the galaxy on behalf of Tomorrowland Transit Authority.â€ <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Read more at: <br/> <s>http://www.geekwire.com/2015/google-teams-disney-make-intergalactic-cartoon-inspire-kids-code/'),
(209, '<img src="uploads/mridula/projectnotesPic/2015-02-06_09:06:41am_2050pawnshoop.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> For most of us, trying to picture the future is a futile exercise that leads at best to some bad ideas that should likely never be shared out loud. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>One recent project challenged visitors to the Museum for Arts and Design in New York to come up with products you might find in a pawn shop in 2050. Like all good science fiction, the results riff off things that are already shimmering in the real world. And like all good science fiction, some of them are more than a little bonkers. A nice twist? You can buy them all, with profits going toward researchers working in that particular area. Here, take a look at 16 objects that donâ€™t exist yet â€¦ but might. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>1. A robot frog to replace those wiped out by disease: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The artificial, bio-robotic â€œAnura-43â€³ frog replaces flesh-and-blood counterparts that had become extinct by 2050. Sadly, the loss isnâ€™t entirely that unlikely: as The Guardian has reported, a fungus epidemic first threatened frogs in Costa Rica in 1987 and it now threatens nearly 3,000 amphibian species. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>2. A gizmo to design your children (and your childrenâ€™s children): <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Genetic engineering has provided the basis of much moral handwringing and discussion (see this interview with ethics professor Julian Savulescu). By 2050, concepts such as genetic terrorism and â€œsterility suicide bombersâ€ will likely have become unnervingly familiar. The â€œClean Gene Machineâ€ allows people to visualize and understand all the genetic permutations that could result from their reproducing â€” and be rid of any unwanted glitches that might result in their children being infertile. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>3. A robotic drone to bring you â€¦ yogurt: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Even by 2015, companies were excitedly trumpeting the potential of drones (or â€œunmanned aerial vehicles,â€ as their makers would rather you called them) to transform lives for the better or, at least, bring you stuff now. (See the TED playlist Will drones save us or destroy us?) By 2050, the â€œDro-Yoâ€ could do both through the drone-delivery of yogurt. Why yogurt? Because it might just be the healthiest thing out there. In 2013, Yovivo wanted to use synthetic biology to amp up yogurtâ€™s naturally healthy properties and include clones of resveratrol, the molecule commonly found in red wine that lowers bad cholesterol and improves circulation. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>4. Cookie dough that deflects drones: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Because drones will be everywhere, weâ€™ll also need a way to escape them. Eat the â€œDrone Detection Cookie Doughâ€ and a combination of spider web technology and quartz crystals projects a magical personal biosphere to make you invisible. Downside: this product could make everyone very, very fat. Thatâ€™s why itâ€™s perhaps lucky this one wasnâ€™t based on much more than wishful thinking. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>5. A way to extract gold from sea water: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>According to researchers, â€œmarine water is one of the richest sources of gold in nature.â€ The issue: how to get at it. Using principles of biomimicry, the â€œGold Oysterâ€ borrows the way that regular oysters filter their food from water, only it would filter and extract gold particles (for use in phones, etc). <br/> <s> <br/> <s>6. Contraception that screens embryos: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The â€œNext Choice Inheritâ€ device analyzes embryos and implants only those without genetic predisposition to disease. Ray Kurzweil would be proud. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>7. A sustainable way to build in space: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>In 2014, International Space Station commander Barry Wilmore 3D-printed a ratchet while floating in space, so who knows what weâ€™ll be printing up there by 2050? Another development to track â€” the use of microbes to catalyze life-sustaining products we wonâ€™t want to haul to space. â€œSpacecreteâ€ uses astronaut waste and microbes to bond rocks and dust into a sustainable building material. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>8. The means to knock off a mosquito: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The â€œTele-squitoâ€ allows you to capture mosquitoes, extract their genes and then implant them into other mosquitoes. Why would you want to do this, you ask yourself? There are good reasons. Really. As Michael Specter (TED Talk: The danger of science denial) reported in the New Yorker in 2012, the firm Oxitec has been working on a way to modify the dengue-carrying Aedes mosquito so that the mutant version essentially destroys its own species. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>9. An orchestra played by bugs: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>â€œThe Critter Orchestraâ€ basically means you could program small animals (insects, frogs, etc.) to play music. Once again, this crazy-sounding idea is rooted in reality: as Ed Yong (TED Talk: Zombie roaches and other parasite tales) has detailed, the protozoa Toxoplasma gondii can cause personality changes in its host, not always to as benign effect as getting it to bang out â€œYankee Doodle Dandyâ€ â€¦ <br/> <s> <br/> <s>10. A device to record memories: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The â€œVirtusenseâ€ directly connects to your brain via the neck. Why? To capture and retain memories that otherwise might be lost to time. (Given increased life expectancy, weâ€™ll all have a lot to remember.) One interesting question â€” what happens when the device is separated from the person? Will we be able to borrow or buy someone elseâ€™s experiences? <br/> <s> <br/> <s>11. An energy carbon credit calculator â€¦ that pays off the national debt: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>â€œBy 2039, federal debt held by the public would reach 106 percent of GDP, more than in any year except 1946,â€ estimated an uncheering 2014 report from the Congressional Budget Office. The â€œWattexchangeâ€ helps to offset this alarming number via a calculator that allows individuals to buy and sell carbon credits. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>12. A way to mess with someoneâ€™s memories: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>â€œNightmare Fuelâ€ is a way to replace someoneâ€™s perfectly happy memories with, well, with nightmares. Riffing off the 2013 discovery by scientists at MIT that we have a gene that replaces old memories with new ones, this product is the bad, bad application of that insight. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>13. A way to overwrite your driverless carâ€™s fateful decisions: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The â€œEthx Overwriteâ€ is an add-on for Tesla cars (the 2040 driverless models). It allows drivers to bypass the carâ€™s decisions, such as the one deciding which driver would die in an unavoidable fatal accident. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>14. A way to test whether life is sustainable: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>This small machine, known as an â€œExo-Life,â€ uses organisms to see whether life in new environments on exoplanets and space stations is viable or not. This riffs off research from NASA and others that would allow pioneers to â€œbuild a Mars base with a box of engineered bugs.â€ <br/> <s> <br/> <s>15. A custom-made pill to change your personality: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Forget the gym. Never mind meditation. The â€œMicro-mindâ€ is a microbial supplement to change your personality in any way you like. (In 2013, scientists posited that the makeup of bacteria in the human might affect not only body weight but also the brain.) <br/> <s> <br/> <s>16. A cleaner that eats dirt and dust: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Whoâ€™s to say that James Dyson and his merry band of inventors in the UK arenâ€™t already working on a vacuum cleaner thatâ€™s, you know, alive? The â€œDyson DC99 Cobraâ€ is a living, hanging organism that resembles a plant â€” and eats hair and dust to minimize cleaning and maximize sparkliness. <br/> <s>Reference and Pics: http://ideas.ted.com/16-objects-you-might-find-in-a-pawn-shop-in-2050/'),
(210, '<img src="uploads/shruti/photoPic/2015-02-06_10:19:47am_mindset.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> When it comes to brilliant leadership, there<r>s no cookie-cutter mold for success. Vastly divergent styles can work equally well, which explains why many of our most respected leaders in business and tech often fall on opposite sides of a large number of spectrums. <s><br/> <s>But while their styles may vary, successful leaders share very similar mindsets: <br/> <s>That<r>s the takeaway from Gap International, a global business consulting firm that conducted in-depth interviews with more than 500 global executives over the past two-years to get a sense of a leader<r>s mindset at the time he or she recalls doing excellent, productive work. <br/> <s>Exceptional outcomes were also achieved when leaders actively focused on their team members. Successful executives knew that to achieve greatness, they needed to ensure that those working below them were also highly motivated. <br/> <s>leaders focused on the impact their actions had on the world and people around them: <br/> <s>Content source: http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/238858'),
(211, '<img src="uploads/shruti/projectnotesPic/2015-02-07_07:39:56am_vivaldi.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> The new Vivaldi internet browser was downloaded 500,000 times in its first 10 days of operation, the company told Reuters on Friday. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Launched on Jan. 27 for desktop computers, Vivaldi targets users who conduct a large number of searches, offering features like speed dials, personalised notes and bookmarks with small screen shots. <br/> <s> <br/> <s><a>quot;It<r>s a very high number, especially if you consider that it<r>s still a technical preview,<a>quot; founder and Chief Executive Jon von Tetzchner said. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>When launching the browser, von Tetzchner, who owns 90 percent of the company, said it only needed <a>quot;a few million users<a>quot; to become profitable in a market dominated by household names like Google<r>s (GOOGL.O) Chrome, Microsoft<r>s (MSFT.O) Internet Explorer, Mozilla Corp<r>s Firefox, Apple<r>s (AAPL.O) Safari and Opera Software (OPERA.OL). <br/> <s> <br/> <s>So far Vivaldi has been made available for desktop computers on Windows, Mac and Linux, with a mobile and tablet version in the pipeline.'),
(212, '<img src="uploads/shruti/projectnotesPic/2015-02-07_07:48:31am_ubuntusmartphone.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> European customers will be the first to get their hands on an Ubuntu phone. <br/> <s>The Aquaris E4.5 Ubuntu Edition will retail for â‚¬169.90 and be sold via BQ.com through a series of flash sales. <br/> <s>Keep an eye on the Ubuntu and BQ Twitter accounts for the date, time, and URL of the first sale; details will also be posted to the Ubuntu Google  and Facebook pages within the next week. <br/> <s><a>quot;The launch of the first Ubuntu smartphones is a significant milestone,<a>quot; Canonical CEO Jane Silber said in a statement. <br/> <s>Canonical announced the open-source Ubuntu operating system early in 2013, with a focus on the enterprise market and basic, entry-level smartphones. At the time, Silber envisioned the OS for basic tasks like phone, SMS, Web, and email. <br/> <s>Already past its 2014 deadline, Canonical today revealed the Aquaris E4.5, with a 4.5-inch screen and the Scopes mobile UI, which presents digital life services (music, social, Web, photos, etc.) on the home screen. <br/> <s>The device has 8GB of storage, a 5-megapixel front camera and 8-megapixel rear shooter with autofocus and dual flash, as well as full HD for super-sharp video. <br/> <s>It also features a MediaTek quad-core Cortex A7 processor running at up to 1.3GHz and 1GB of RAM. It<r>s a dual-SIM device and comes unlocked for use on any network. Operators like 3 Sweden, amena.com in Spain, giffgaff in the U.K., and Portugal Telecom are offering SIM bundles with the purchase of the phone. <br/> <s><a>quot;Ubuntu presents users with an entirely different way to engage with their devicesâ€”Scopes guide you to content you want, in the same way you think about itâ€”to deliver a smooth, engaging experience,<a>quot; said Cristian Parrino, vice president of mobile. <br/> <s>Developers will have a field day with Scopes, Parrino said, touting it as a <a>quot;much simpler and more valuable<a>quot; way to build mobile experiences. <br/> <s>Content from http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2476410,00.asp'),
(213, '<img src="uploads/shruti/projectnotesPic/2015-02-07_07:53:54am_gtalk.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Gtalk will breathe its last on February 16 and whoosh! Like all good things, Gtalk will become history (just like how Orkut has been). <br/> <s> <br/> <s>In two weeks from now, you<r>ll have to make the switch from Google<r>s Gtalk messenger platform to its Hangout (whether they like it or not). Millions of users have been using the Gtalk for long time and they<r>ve become so comfortable with it that moving away has never been considered. So, Google has decided to force users by shutting down Gtalk once and for all. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Hangout is the future for Google (so they seem to think) and hence taking down Gtalk is the most logical thing that the search-engine giant can do now. Signs of Gtalk going down became obvious when Google decided to cut support (security and version) for the desktop application bringing its end closer to reality. As highlighted by Google the <r>IM service will be wholly replaced by the Hangouts app, which can used only via its Chrome web browser.'),
(214, '<img src="uploads/rajnish/photoPic/2015-02-07_08:05:36am_howmuchtime.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> People Sleep 1/3 of Their Lives: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The one activity people spend the most time on is sleep. If you live 78 years, 28.3 of those you will be asleep. So what? If your startup finds a way to improve sleep, your customers will be using your product every day, for 1/3 of their lives. If you improve the quality of their sleep, help them get rid of nightmares, you can say you have served humanity well. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>People Spend 6 Years of Life Unhappily- <s>Doing chores: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Who likes doing chores? A startup that mops your floor, washes the dishes, etc. could save you 6 years of life. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>People Spend 9 Years Entertaining Themselves.: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>If people play almost as much as they work even though they are getting paid for work but not for play, there is something that can be done to make work more fun. This starts with education â€“ a person who loves their job often finds it as satisfying as playing. But not everyone does. Far from that. It does not have to be this way if you help more people find the job that they would really like. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Almost Half of World Population Donâ€™t Have a Job: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The largest single group of people, kids, are too young to work. How will our world change once these kids grow up in a few years and add almost two billion brains to the global workforce? Will the price of labor go down? Will they be doing new jobs that donâ€™t exist yet? Or will they even have any skills that would make them employable? <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Every Fifth Human is Still Farming: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Having a job was not always the default way to make money. 100 years ago farming was the default thing to do in life. Today every fifth human is still doing it. It makes sense because someone does need to grow the food we eat. But as more robots drive agricultural growth, humans could not and would not want to compete. So what will they do? <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Almost Half a Billion Entrepreneurs: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>If having a job is the current default way to make money, you have got to ask what will be the next? One group of humans stands out â€“ the 400 million entrepreneurs. These are anyone from a fruit stand entrepreneur to a founder of a bank. One thing they have in common is that they did not look for a job, they created one for themselves. This is likely the future way of living. Most people who can create a job for themselves will, and others will look for one. Of course the world will not look like 10 billion one-person startups, but the ratio we see now will change. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>What Can You Do Today?: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>These images are a snapshot of the world today. It will not stay this way. So if you are learning something, getting a degree, building a startup, or getting a job, a <s>good question to ask is: Am I learning and building for tomorrowâ€™s world or for todayâ€™s? <br/> <s>http://fundersandfounders.com/what-7-billion-world-population-does/');
