(236, '<img src="uploads/shruti/projectnotesPic/2015-02-12_01:08:47pm_inteliotroadshow_png.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Are you ready to build something innovative with IntelÂ® IoT Developer Kit ? Hereâ€™s your chance to win the prize ! <br/> <s> <br/> <s>When ? <s>14-15 March 2015 <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Where ? <s>Bangalore, India <br/> <s> <br/> <s>In 2015 IntelÂ® is hosting 20 IoT Roadshow events for developer communities in cities across the US, Europe, South American and Asia. We are updating our schedule for the first half of the year, please see below for our upcoming events. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Where do I register? <s>http://iotroadshow.intel.com. <s><br/> <s>The registration on the website is obligatory in order to participate in the hackathon. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>If youâ€™re a maker, an IoT startup, a developer, a student or a hardware novice, join us, get your free* Dev Kit, which includes an IntelÂ® development board, and begin building something awesome! <br/> <s> <br/> <s>In addition to providing you with the Dev Kits, tools, tasty food, giveaways on-site, and prizes** also provided for the best IoT solutions. <br/> <s>Free Dev Kits will be limited to the first 100 people who check-in at each event. <br/> <s>check for more details and registration https://iotroadshow.intel.com/en/home/'),
(237, '<iframe class="youtube" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/V4UQU4392wM "frameborder="0" allowfullscreen ></iframe><br/> Max Oritz Catalan is dedicated to making prosthesis better. At TEDxGÃ¶teborg, the researcher explains how his group at Chalmers University of Technology in Sweden is working to make that happen â€” through bone-anchored robotic prosthetics controlled by implanted electrodes. <br/> <s>Most bionic limbs operate through surface electrodes attached to a patientâ€™s skin, Oritz Catalan says, and these surface-mounted electrodes offer patients limited control. <br/> <s>Oritz Catalanâ€™s new device improves the prosthetic experience through two main ways, he says. One, the device is anchored in bone, rather than attached by compressing a limb socket. â€œWe move from suspension to fixation,â€ he says, â€œwhich is a lot better mechanical coupling â€” we get rid of the problems related to the socket,â€ like blistering and painful friction. And, two, says Oritz Catalan, the device offers users greater mobility through the use of implanted electrodes rather than surface ones. <br/> <s>Read more at: http://tedxinnovations.ted.com/2015/02/12/spotlight-tedx-talk-robotic-limbs-you-control-with-your-mind/'),
(238, '<img src="uploads/shruti/projectnotesPic/2015-02-13_07:24:43am_nottosay.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Thereâ€™s plenty advice out there to rehearse what youâ€™re going to say in a job interview: research questions the interviewer might ask, practice your answers, come up with salient questions of your ownâ€¦ <br/> <s> <br/> <s>But what about rehearsing what youâ€™re not going to say? <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Here is a list below of some words youâ€™ll want to try to avoid at your next job interview, because even though they seem like just ordinary words, they could be major red flags for an interviewer or recruiter. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>1. No: <br/> <s>First of all, if asked even a simple question, you donâ€™t want to give a single word answer (yes or no). But when the answer is no, definitely donâ€™t leave it there! For example, if asked if you know a particular computer program, and you donâ€™t, you could say, â€œI haven<r>t yet had a chance to learn it but would be interested to do so,â€ rather than simply saying â€œNo.â€ <br/> <s> <br/> <s>2. Erâ€¦ Umâ€¦: <br/> <s>That old saying, â€œIf you donâ€™t have anything to say, donâ€™t say anything at all,â€ applies here a big. Rather than hemming and hawing while you try to think up an answer, just be silent and think. Saying er or um too much could make you seem unprepared or as though youâ€™re not paying attention. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>3. Whatever, OMG, baeâ€¦ groovy?: <br/> <s>Lose the slang when talking to an interviewer. You want to come across as polished and professional, and you donâ€™t want them to have to dig out their urban dictionary to understand you. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>4. Sure, cool, kindaâ€¦: <br/> <s>These kinds of words are just too casual, even in a casual workplace. You should be presenting the best version of yourself, not the sloppy, casual version. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>5. We: <br/> <s>This one seems innocuous at first, but if you use it a lot when discussing job duties and accomplishments, the interviewer might start to wonder if it was you or your team that was responsible. Try to use â€œIâ€ as much as possible. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>6. Dedicated, motivated, team player...: <br/> <s>Lose the resume speech and jargon. Besides the fact that these words are incredibly overused in interview situations, theyâ€™re also better demonstrated than just stated. If you want to convey your dedication or motivation, share an example from your past work experience; examples will go much further to making your claims believable. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>7. Leverage, synergy, ideationâ€¦: <br/> <s>Iâ€™d avoid using too much business jargon. The chances that youâ€™ll come off sounding like an idiot are just too high. Too much business buzzwords or jargon tends to make people sound pretentious, or worse, downright stupid. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>8. <r>Hit the ground running,<r> <r>Circle backâ€¦<r>: <br/> <s>These kinds of cliches have little to no meaning, theyâ€™re just verbal fluff, and they donâ€™t add anything to what youâ€™re saying. So leave them out. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>9. Hate: <br/> <s>I canâ€™t think of a single instance when saying you â€œhateâ€ something in a job interview is appropriate, but itâ€™s exceptionally inappropriate to say anything about hating your former job, co-workers, boss, etc. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>10. Perfectionist: <br/> <s>Itâ€™s become almost a cliche in and of itself to answer a question like, â€œWhatâ€™s your biggest flaw?â€ with a positive flaw like, â€œIâ€™m a perfectionist.â€ Any good interviewer will see right through that, so just donâ€™t do it. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>This would really helpful for cracking interview. Only technical skills are not enough for getting good job. <br/> <s>Reference: https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/10-toxic-words-you-must-say-job-interview-bernard-marr <br/> <s>Check more: http://www.businessinsider.in/13-Things-You-Should-Never-Say-In-A-Job-Interview/articleshow/39637539.cms'),
(239, '<img src="uploads/mridula/articlePic/2015-02-13_09:00:02am_creativeconfidence.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Think about your organization for a moment and consider these two questions:-- <br/> <s> <br/> <s>How good is your organization at execution?: <br/> <s>How prepared do you feel your organization is to drive innovation?: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>As young children, weâ€™re all creative. We draw, sing, build, and dream. Yet somewhere along the way, many peopleâ€™s creativity gets blocked, and we start to say, â€œIâ€™m not the creative type.â€ <br/> <s> <br/> <s>If youâ€™re like most people I pose these questions to, your answers to both probably fall somewhere around good, pretty good, or very good. But you might also add that you could stand to do better. <br/> <s>Most organizations want to consistently do innovation. Executives and managers feel it is critical to the success of their organization or business. But even though they know it is necessary to survive, many donâ€™t know how to go about it. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Hereâ€™s one equation for innovation that I like: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Creativity * Execution = Innovation: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>A company may be able to execute, but without creativity there is no innovation. The same holds true for creative organizations that lack the ability to execute. <br/> <s>Design thinking is taught at the d.school as a five-stage process. It starts with developing empathy for your user and goes on to defining the problem, brainstorming potential solutions, rapidly prototyping one or more of those proposed solutions, and then testing that prototype with your user. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>A new concept has emerged out of the d.school, however. Itâ€™s called creative confidence, and I think it better captures what organizations need to establish or grow their innovation capacity. Creative confidence is what design thinking brings to an organization. <br/> <s>I often find people believe innovation is about problem solving. Really though, innovation is about problem finding. There are countless problems to be solved, but only a fraction of those will lead to great innovations. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Innovation is also about education. This means organizations need to emphasize the value <br/> <s>of free and open learning and discovery. They should challenge employees to consistently seek out knowledge in order to help them identify new problems to solve. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>If you want to do innovation, foster creative confidence within your organization. Focus on education and problem finding. The greatest innovations come not from process and execution, but from finding the relevant problem worth solving. <br/> <s>See more at: http://www.news-sap.com/creative-confidence-drives-innovation'),
(240, '<img src="uploads/anil/projectnotesPic/2015-02-13_09:21:43am_boom.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> TONY COLES COULD have had any job he wanted in the drug industry. In five years at the helm of cancer drug developer Onyx Pharmaceuticals he increased its market cap eightfold by purchasing an experimental blood cancer drug for $800 million, developing it into a big seller and flipping the whole company to Amgen for $10.4 billion in October 2013. He personally made $60 million on the deal. Biotech watchers expected him to start another cancer company or even command a drug giant like Merck or Pfizer. <br/> <s>Instead, Coles, 54, is using his own money to build a Cambridge, Mass.-based startup called Yumanity that is using yeast, the microbes that help make bread and beer, to study how misfolded proteins in the brain cause Alzheimerâ€™s, Lou Gehrigâ€™s disease and Parkinsonâ€™s, and to create drugs based on that knowledge. Thereâ€™s already interest from Big Pharma. Coles says he chose to attack brain diseases, not tumors, because the need is so dire and the science is so fresh. <br/> <s>Read full article at: http://www.forbes.com/sites/matthewherper/2015/02/11/brain-boom-the-drug-companies-bringing-neuroscience-back-from-the-brink/'),
(241, '<img src="uploads/anil/challengePic/2015-02-13_10:46:43am_scriptkid.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /> <br/> Script kids: <br/> <s> Usually <s>teenagers , with minimal knowledge of computer systems that executes code or follows procedures created by more knowledgeable people to break into computer systems.The script kids flies in the face of all that the hacker subculture stands for - the pursuit of knowledge, respect for skills, and motivation to self-teach are just three of the hacker ideals that the script kids ignores. While anyone can be a script kid, generally <s>who want the power of the hacker without the discipline or training involved. A script kid is not looking to target specific information or a specific company but rather uses knowledge of a vulnerability to scan the entire Internet for a victim that possesses that vulnerability. These kids are often portrayed by the media and other non-technically savvy parties as being very intelligent and having tremendous technical knowledge despite the fact that very few of these so-called <a>quot;hackers<a>quot; can write their own computer programs or even possess even the most rudimentary technical understanding of the underlying systems that they are attacking or using. The wide-spread and trivial availability of these scripts for <a>quot;hacking<a>quot; allows these kids to cause serious problems from time-to-time and thus they get themselves into trouble way out of proportion to their skill set. To leap to the assumption that one of these script kids has significant computer knowledge based on his ability to successfully execute scripts created by other people is equivalent to assuming that the functionally-illiterate 14 year old that shoots a clerk at a convenience store must be a physics expert because he managed to fire a gun. <br/> <s>Programmers: <br/> <s>Computer programmers write, test, debug, and maintain the detailed instructions, called computer programs, that computers must follow to perform their functions. Programmers also conceive, design, and test logical structures for solving problems by computer. Many technical innovations in programming â€” advanced computing technologies and sophisticated new languages and programming tools â€” have redefined the role of a programmer and elevated much of the programming work done today. Job titles and descriptions may vary, depending on the organization. <s>Programmers are essential to the development of computers because without the coding that is necessary to make a computer work properly, the machine would be useless. Programmers may specialize in one area or may write instructions for a wide range of systems or programs. Programmer who cracks (gains unauthorized access to) computers, typically to do malicious things; <a>quot;crackers are often mistakenly called hackers<a>quot; called Cracker. Programmer for whom computing is its own reward; may enjoy the challenge of breaking into other computers but does no harm; <a>quot;true hackers subscribe to a code of ethics and look down upon crackers<a>quot; called Hacker.'),
(242, '<iframe class="youtube" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/xrAuNRLeAQk "frameborder="0" allowfullscreen ></iframe><br/> Some years ago when the Communist government in China started building up and modernizing their military their neighbors in Asia were concerned. To alleviate the fears of their neighbors the commies stated their military buildup was purely for peace. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The problem is China<r>s neighbors thought they meant <a>quot;peace,<a>quot; when what they really meant was <a>quot;piece.<a>quot; A piece of the Philippines (Scarborough Shoal). A piece of Vietnam (territorial waters off Vietnam). A piece of Japan (the Senkaku Islands). A piece of India (invading the border region between the two nations). <br/> <s>- <br/> <s>The United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea -- UNCLOS, establishes a 200 mile Exclusive Economic Zone -- EEZ, off the coast of nations out to the sea. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>However the commies in China have a different interpretation of reality. They are ignoring the EEZ<r>s established by the United Nations and established their own zone claiming virtually all of the South China Sea. They are blatantly violating the EEZ<r>s of Vietnam, Malaysia, Indonesia, Malaysia, Brunei, and the Philippines. With the Spratly Islands belonging to Japan, the commies are claiming these islands also. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The Scarborough Shoal within the Philippine EEZ has been forcibly stolen by the Chinese. This land / water grab has ruined the livelihood of many Filipinos in the Western Philippines. The government of the Philippines allowed China<r>s aggressive, bully behavior according to the article (link below) because China<r>s military is too massive. The peaceful or piece-full commie military with evil sinister designs on their neighbors. Remember, commies never make good neighbors. <br/> <s>- <br/> <s>United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea: <br/> <s>http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_N... <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Article refer