(253, '<img src="uploads/anil/projectnotesPic/2015-02-17_08:05:53am_danaguide.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Prostheses, bionic implants, and drugs are creating new neural signals and novel experiences of the world. And it turns out, discovering how to build a sense from scratch is one step closer to amplifying it. Infrared vision, hypertactile sensitivity, and Jaime Sommers-level hearing. <s><br/> <s>Hearing: <br/> <s>The ear amplifies sound waves to jiggle the jellylike fluid inside the cochleaâ€”which translates to neural auditory signals. An electrode array in a cochlear implant receives input from a behind-the-ear speech processor and stimulates the auditory nerve. <br/> <s>Smell : <br/> <s>Hundreds of olfactory receptors in the nose respond to different smells; what they pick up gets integrated in the brainâ€™s olfactory bulb.Corticosteroids can ease the swelling of tissue around the olfactory bulb that robs some people of their sense of smell. <br/> <s>Sight : <br/> <s>The lens focuses light onto the retina at the back of the eye, where millions of nerve endings turn it into electrical impulses that travel down the optic nerve. A camera sends a 60-pixel grayscale image to a postage-stamp-sized electrode implant, which bypasses damaged retinal cells to send signals to the optic nerve. <br/> <s>Embodiment : <br/> <s>The brain integrates senses like touch, vision, and proprioception to create a feeling of ownership of our body parts. Reroute severed arm nerves to another location on an amputeeâ€™s body, like the chest. <br/> <s>Touch : <br/> <s> Receptors react to pressure, texture, vibration, temperature, and pain, signaling the brain via neurons throughout the body. Pressure sensors on the fingertips of prosthetic hands can send signals to electrodes implanted around remaining nerves. <s><br/> <s>Proprioception : <br/> <s> Proprioception combines sensations so you know your bodyâ€™s position in space. Scientists donâ€™t fully understand how it works, but it involves muscle receptors that monitor length, tension, and pressure. People with spinal cord injuries that disrupt proprioception can relearn where their arms and legs are by using a robotic exoskeleton. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Source : http://www.wired.com '),
(254, '<img src="uploads/mridula/projectnotesPic/2015-02-17_01:25:34pm_google.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> If youâ€™ve got a smartphone, you definitely access the internet from your device- if youâ€™ve got sufficient data plans. McKinsey analyzed data, and data from the International Labor Organization, a survey involving around 8,000 smartphone owners revealed that expensive data is among one of the biggest reasons why people hesitate in downloading or using apps on their phones. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>According to a report from The Information, Google might be looking to capitalization of data costs, so that people actually use their smartphones- lucrative apps are amazing and everything, but keeping up with them or downloading them is a headache with current plans. Over 25% of the people surveyed from India, Thailand, Egypt, Indonesia and Philippines face this problem during their smartphone experience. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Engineers at Google have been discussing the idea with app developers in these developing markets to enable reduction, and possible cost elimination of data, using something called â€˜zero ratingâ€™- a practice where mobile network operators do not charge end customers for a pre specified data volume for specific applications or internet services, via the operatorâ€™s wireless network in metered data plans and tariffs. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Enter Google- it reportedly has plans to launch this gambit in India, involving some of the biggies like Rebus, Flipkart, Ola cabs among others. Using these apps usually rockets data costs sky high, and developers are ready to bear cost overheads for them. This â€˜zero ratingâ€™ system is expected to roll-out from Googleâ€™s low-budget initiative launched in India last year, the Android One. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>What will actually go on is- when you access Flipkart on your phone, Google will identify and track your data costs and pay your carrier for them, along with the third party developer, which will be expected to carry some of the overheads. Google is the intermediary here- app developers will not have to make zero rating arrangements with individual providers.'),
(255, 'All of these functions read a character from input and return an integer value. The integer is returned to accommodate a special value used to indicate failure. The value EOF is generally used for this purpose. <s><br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â getc(): <s><br/> <s> Â It reads a single character from a given input stream and returns the corresponding integer value (typically ASCII value of read character) on success. It returns EOF on failure. <s><br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â Syntax: <s><br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â int getc(FILE *stream); Â  <br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â Example: <s><br/> <s> Â // Example for getc() in C <s><br/> <s> Â #include <a>lt;stdio.h<a>gt; <s><br/> <s> Â int main() <s><br/> <s> Â { <s><br/> <s> Â  Â  printf(<a>quot;%c<a>quot;, getc(stdin)); <s><br/> <s> Â  Â  return(0); <s><br/> <s> Â } <s><br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â Input: g (press enter key) <s><br/> <s> Â Output: g Â  <br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â getchar(): <s><br/> <s> Â The difference between getc() and getchar() is getc() can read from any input stream, but getchar() reads from standard input. So getchar() is equivalent to getc(stdin). <s><br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â Syntax: <s><br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â int getchar(void); Â  <br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â Example: <s><br/> <s> Â // Example for getchar() in C <s><br/> <s> Â #include <a>lt;stdio.h<a>gt; <s><br/> <s> Â int main() <s><br/> <s> Â { <s><br/> <s> Â  Â  printf(<a>quot;%c<a>quot;, getchar()); <s><br/> <s> Â  Â  return 0; <s><br/> <s> Â } <s><br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â Input: g(press enter key) <s><br/> <s> Â Output: g Â  <br/> <s> Â  <s><br/> <s> Â getch(): <s><br/> <s> Â getch() is a nonstandard function and is present in conio.h header file which is mostly used by MS-DOS compilers like Turbo C. It is not part of the C standard library or ISO C, nor is it defined by POSIX (Source: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conio.h) <s><br/> <s> Â Like above functions, it reads also a single character from keyboard. But it does not use any buffer