(259, '<img src="uploads/mridula/challengePic/2015-02-18_05:31:12am_volta.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /> <br/> Volta had created the first electric battery: the Voltaic Pile, a stack of alternating metal discs separated by cardboard and cloth soaked with seawater. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Alessandro Volta was a Lombard <s>physicist known especially for the invention of the battery in 1800. Volta was born in Como, Italy, and taught in the public schools there . <br/> <s> <br/> <s>1774 : He became a physics professor at the Royal School In Como. <s><br/> <s>1775: He improved and popularized the electrophorus, a device that produces a static electric charge. <s><br/> <s>1776-1777 Volta studied the chemistry of gases. He discovered methane by collecting the gas from marshes. He devised experiments such as the ignition of methane by an electric spark in a closed vessel. <a>quot;Alessandro Volta<a>quot; <br/> <s> <br/> <s>In 1800, he invented the VOLTAIC PILE , an early electric battery, which produced a steady electric current. Volta had determined that the most effective pair of dissimilar metals to produce electricity was zinc and silver. Initially he experimented with individual cells in series, each cell being a wine goblet filled with brine into which the two dissimilar electrodes were dipped. The voltaic pile replaced the goblets with cardboard soaked in brine. <a>quot;Alessandro Volta<a>quot;'),
(260, '<img src="uploads/mridula/articlePic/2015-02-18_05:45:54am_usebigdata.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Big data continues to be a heavily discussed topic, but generally it doesnâ€™t make its way into discussions about infrastructure and converged systems. But that doesnâ€™t mean big data doesnâ€™t have a role to play in this arena. There is plenty of data generated about enterprise networks. That data resides in log files, but often is simply discarded. Jonathan Crane, Chief Commercial Officer at IPsoft, believes there is a whole new playing field for IT infrastructure: big data in the internal IT department. <br/> <s>By turning predictive analytics inward to track where breaks happen most frequently, IT and network admins can set more accurate thresholds for recurring issues, positioning themselves ahead of any damage. <br/> <s>Crane says, â€œBy applying data analysis around recurring issues in the network or IT infrastructure, organizations can discover problems that should be proactively addressed, thus reducing instances of, say, performance degradation and bandwidth over-consumption. <br/> <s>â€œResource availability and performance are the two obvious benefits of applying predictive analytics to IT, but more important is the speed at which results can occur. If you consider the management of trading applications in the financial services market, for example, without the aid of big data analytics, a system administrator could take up to an hour to determine why a new trade failed to execute. Over the course of that hour, the trade itself has reduced in value and the revenue opportunity is lost. <br/> <s>â€œAs IT infrastructure becomes increasingly complex, avoiding this slow infrastructure analysis process will be a key concern for CIOs. With greater volumes of recurring instances, and more decisions made within compressed timeframes, administrators can collect enough data to address the factors that cause those instances, and eventually prevent them from happening at all.<a>quot; <br/> <s>Reference: http://www.convergeyourbranch.com/117/use-big-network-data-predict-and-avoid-network-problems-11315'),
