(309, '<img src="uploads/rajnish/projectnotesPic/2015-02-25_04:53:37am_toro.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Toro, a startup that helps developers promote their apps on Facebook, just announced that itâ€™s been acquired by Google. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The company was originally known as Red Hot Labs, and itâ€™s led by Amitt Mahajan and Joel Poloney. They previously co-founded MyMiniLife, which played a key role in the creation of FarmVille (and was acquired by Zynga). <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Mahajan and Poloney told me last fall that the companyâ€™s aim was to make launching and optimizing a Facebook ad campaign as easy as possible for mobile app developers, by automatically creating and testing â€œhundreds of variantsâ€ for each campaign. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>In its announcement, Toro writes that joining Google will provide access to more resources and distribution, allowing the team to â€œcontinue our mission of making the lives of app developers easier.â€ <br/> <s> <br/> <s>If you think this might shift Toroâ€™s focus away from Facebook, well, looks youâ€™re right. The company says it will continue to optimize campaigns and provide reports for existing customers, but it wonâ€™t be creating new campaigns: â€œWe recommend working with an alternative Facebook PMD for new campaigns going forward.â€ <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The announcement does not disclose the financial terms of the deal. Toro had raised $1.5 million in funding from investors including Andreessen Horowitz, Greylock Partners, SV Angel, General Catalyst, Keith Rabois, Chris Dixon, Bill Tai, and Guitar Hero co-creators Charles Huang and Kai Huang'),
(310, '<img src="uploads/rajnish/projectnotesPic/2015-02-25_05:06:40am_headgear.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Technology that allows a drone to be piloted from the ground using only a person<r>s brainwaves has been demonstrated in Portugal. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The company behind the development, Tekever, said the technology could in the short term be used to enable people with restricted movement to control aircraft. <br/> <s>Longer term the firm said piloting of larger jets, such as cargo planes, could be controlled in this way without the need for a crew on board. <br/> <s>However, one aviation expert told the BBC he thought the industry would be unlikely to adopt such technology due to a perception of being potentially unsafe. <br/> <s> <br/> <s><r>Everyday activity<r>: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Drone specialist Tekever, which works with security firms, police forces and the military, adapted existing Electroencephalography (EEG) technology so it could issue instructions to the software used to give the unmanned drone instructions. <br/> <s>EEG works by detecting activity in specific parts of the brain. After several months of training, <a>quot;pilots<a>quot; are said to be able to teach their brain how to think about moving a small circle on a computer screen either up or down, which in turn steers the drone left or right. <br/> <s><a>quot;We believe people will be able to pilot aircraft just like they perform everyday activities like walking or running,<a>quot; said Ricardo Mendes, Tekever<r>s chief operating officer. <br/> <s><a>quot;We truly believe that Brainflight represents the beginning of a tremendous step change in the aviation field, empowering pilots and de-risking missions, and we<r>re looking forward to deliver these benefits to the market with highly innovative products.<a>quot; <br/> <s> <br/> <s><r>Bridge too far<r>: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>In the future, some of this technology may be put to use to control much larger aircraft, although Mr Mendes acknowledged considerable challenges with both regulatory hurdles and public confidence. <br/> <s>Those concerns were echoed by John Strickland, an independent aviation consultant based in London. <br/> <s><a>quot;This to me is certainly at the moment a bridge too far,<a>quot; he told the BBC. <br/> <s><a>quot;You could get someone radically-minded who might say it, but I<r>d be surprised if anyone would do it.<a>quot; <br/> <s>Mr Strickland said the airline industry was instead focusing its innovation efforts towards things like better materials and more economical engines. <br/> <s>Mr Mendes said the technology would incorporate safety measures to counteract the effects of someone having, for example, a seizure while piloting. <br/> <s><a>quot;There are algorithms on board that prevent bad things from happening,<a>quot; he told the BBC. <br/> <s>He added: <a>quot;Technology is evolving, regulations are evolving. [Unmanned jets are] obviously going to happen. The question is not if, it<r>s when.<a>quot; <br/> <s>Watch video at http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-31584547');
