(406, '<img src="uploads/raveesh/projectnotesPic/2015-03-20_09:08:15am_Smartwatchheuer.jpg" style="max-width: 100%;" onError="this.src="img/default.gif"" /><br/> Swiss watchmaker Tag Heuer has announced it is to build an Android Wear-powered smartwatch.: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The firm - which is part of the luxury goods-maker LVMH Group - is forming a partnership with Google and the chipmaker Intel to create the device. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Switzerland dominates the high-end watch sector. This marks the first of its companies to join Google<r>s wearable tech ecosystem. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>One analyst linked the move to Apple<r>s entry into the market. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The announcement was made at the Baselworld trade show in Switzerland. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Jean-Claude Biver, president of LVMH<r>s watch division, told the BBC that it made sense to look beyond Switzerland<r>s borders once his firm had decided to enter the smartwatch market. <br/> <s> <br/> <s><r>Palpable buzz<r>: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>About 720,000 watches powered by Android Wear were shipped in 2014, according to market research firm Canalys. <br/> <s>To date fitness tracking wristbands have outsold the smartwatch sector as a whole by a wide margin. <s><br/> <s> <br/> <s>Emotional smartwatch: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>The Swiss firm has not revealed any images of what the device will look like yet. <br/> <s>But Mr Biver suggested it would stand out from other smartwatches. <br/> <s><a>quot;The whole look of the watch will be different,<a>quot; he said. <br/> <s> <br/> <s><r>Fusion<r>: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Fossil signalled that it would take a similar approach to creating a diverse portfolio of tech-enhanced wristwear. <br/> <s><a>quot;There are many many products coming to market that all look the same,<a>quot; said Theresa Palermo, a marketing executive at Fossil, at the firm<r>s Baselworld press conference. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Fossil recently reported a 1% year-on-year drop in watch sales at a time many of its rivals were reporting growth. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>It accounts for about 6% of all watch sale revenues, according to market research firm Euromonitor, making it one of the five biggest firms in the sector. <s><br/> <s>Story via http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-31966684'),
(407, '<iframe class="youtube" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/N70hnXefg9k "frameborder="0" allowfullscreen ></iframe><br/> Mobile payments are catching on, with apps such as Apple Pay that let you upload your credit card information by photographing the card. But could snapping a photo of your card be putting you at risk for identity theft? <br/> <s> <br/> <s><a>quot;In here it just shows my virtual credit card, I can click on it, I can see my last transaction,<a>quot; says iPhone user Peter Elia, showing how he uses Apple<r>s mobile wallet app, Apple Pay. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>He<r>s excited about the new technology. <a>quot;I think it<r>s the best idea ever, because I hate carrying a wallet and a phone.<a>quot; <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Elia is part of a growing class of cardless consumers driving the mobile payment market. <a>quot;It<r>s growing rapidly and by 2020 it<r>s estimated to be worth $1.4 billion,<a>quot; says Lucie Greene, worldwide director of market research firm JWT Intelligence. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>While mobile payments are catching on, the technology is also raising questions about security and privacy. Forty percent of respondents surveyed by JWT Intelligence said they were â€œvery concernedâ€ about fraud when paying with a mobile phone. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Apple Pay, Google wallet and PayPal all allow you to use your smartphoneâ€™s camera to upload credit card information to the app. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>But could snapping a photo of your card be putting you at risk? <br/> <s> <br/> <s>We asked cyber-security expert Robert Stroud. <a>quot;The difference between just taking a photo with the camera and the app is the app creates a secure environment or a secure session with the process of uploading the information from your credit card or debit card,<a>quot; says Stroud, international president of ISACA, an association for security professionals. <a>quot;At that point in time, the card information is not actually stored in your recent photos or anywhere on the phone, so you donâ€™t have it to be found later.<a>quot; <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Stroud says mobile wallets are actually safer than current credit cards -- because of the way financial information is sent between the app and the bank, replacing your account number with a token. <br/> <s> <br/> <s><a>quot;The tokenization is a form of encryption or scrambling of card information that allows the application itself to understand who you are and what you are so it can then do the transaction,<a>quot; explains Stroud. <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Peter Elia says he likes the convenience of mobile wallets and is not too concerned about his information getting out because he knows heâ€™s protected. <a>quot;Credit cards â€“ it<r>s money, it can be replaced, it<r>s covered by insurance, it<r>s covered by a bank,<a>quot; he says. <br/> <s> <br/> <s><a>quot;Vendors are staking their reputations on it, they<r>re going to make sure it<r>s secure,<a>quot; says Stroud. <a>quot;You<r>re protected in a credit card situation by fraud control and the monitoring thatâ€™s going on 24/7.<a>quot; <br/> <s> <br/> <s>Stroud offers these basic rules to keep your information safe: <br/> <s> <br/> <s>â€¢ Only download and install apps from a trusted source. <br/> <s>â€¢ Pay attention to permission requests from apps. Think twice if it<r>s asking for, say, access to your contacts or other features that seem open to abuse. <br/> <s>â€¢ Make use of all security features on your phone and mobile wallet, andâ€¦ <br/> <s> <br/> <s><a>quot;You have to ensure that that password security<r>s in place, and that you<r>re consistently ensuring that you change your passwords and you keep them sufficiently complex so that they can<r>t be guessed very easily,<a>quot; he says.');
